# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1908-new-york-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The **1908 New York Giants season** was the 26th season of the franchise.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in second place in the National League with a 98–56 record, one game behind the Chicago Cubs.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Paced by Turkey Mike Donlin, the offense scored the most runs in the league.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Donlin led the team in nearly all batting categories and was second in batting to Honus Wagner.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Giants' pitching shut out the opposition 25 times, a franchise record for 1901 onwards.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Future Hall of Famer Christy Mathewson earned the pitching triple crown with 37 wins, 259 strikeouts, and a 1.43 ERA.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] However, he lost the last game of the season to Three Finger Brown of the Chicago Cubs, and the Giants finished one game back in the pennant race.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] That one-game playoff became necessary after Giants rookie Fred Merkle failed to touch second base at the end of a previous contest, costing them a win.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] In addition, they were beaten by another rookie, Phillies pitcher Harry Coveleski, three times in five days late in the season.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Coveleski was subsequently nicknamed "The Giant Killer".
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Giants opened the season on the road with a 3–1 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Giants took five of their first six games of the season.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The home opener at the Polo Grounds was the biggest in club history, as the Giants attracted over 25,000 fans.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Brooklyn Superbas took a 2–1 lead into the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Fred Merkle pinch hit for Christy Mathewson and got a ground rule double.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Merkle safely advanced to third base on a sacrifice bunt.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Fred Tenney hit a grounder and Merkle was caught off third.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Captain Donlin hit a two-run home run over the right field wall to win the home opener for the Giants by a score of 3–2.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] On July 4, Hooks Wiltse had a perfect game heading into the ninth inning.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] With two out in the ninth, the perfect game was still intact.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] George McQuillan was hit by a pitch and Wiltse lost the perfect game. on August 27, the Giants won 18 of their last 23 (including four in a row versus the Pittsburgh Pirates) to take the lead in the National League for the first time since April.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] During the Giants four-game sweep of the Pirates in late August, the electric scoreboard made its debut in New York.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The first electric scoreboard was outside Madison Square Garden, and there was another near the Gotham Theatre on 125th Street.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] In the bottom of the 9th inning, he came up to bat with two outs, and the score tied 1–1.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] At the time, Moose McCormick was on first base.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Merkle singled, and McCormick advanced to third.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Al Bridwell, the next batter, followed with a single of his own.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] McCormick went home, apparently scoring the winning run of the game.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The fans in attendance, under the impression that the game was over, ran onto the field to celebrate.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Meanwhile, Merkle, trying to escape the mob of people, ran to the Giants' clubhouse without touching second base.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Cubs second baseman Johnny Evers noticed this, and after retrieving a ball and touching second base, he appealed to umpire Hank O'Day to call Merkle out.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The validity of the ball was disputed – numerous accounts have Giants pitcher Joe McGinnity intercepting the real ball before Evers could get it.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] However, since Merkle had not touched the base, the umpire called him out on a force play, and McCormick's run did not count.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Since the run was nullified, the Giants' victory was erased, and the score of the game remained tied.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Unfortunately, the thousands of fans on the field (as well as the growing darkness in the days before large electric light rigs made night games possible) prevented resumption of the game, and it was declared a tie.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Giants and the Cubs would end the season deadlocked atop the standings and would have a rematch at the Polo Grounds, on October 8.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] The Cubs won this makeup game, 4–2, and thus the National League pennant.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] Giants manager John McGraw never blamed Merkle for the second-place finish.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/1908-new-york-giants-season] However, the rookie was hounded by the New York press and fans for years thereafter.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1908-new-york-giants-season/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
